Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.08,0:01:45.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Operations at Midway and the Aleutian Islands were carried out in June 1942 by the main force of the Japanese Navy.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.98,0:01:50.93,Default,,0,0,0,,The Midway Operation ended in a devastating defeat for the Japanese armed forces, the first one of this war.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.17,0:02:03.10,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1500,2000)\c&HFCE8E1&\bord0\blur1\pos(624,402)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.17,0:02:03.10,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1500,2000)\c&HFCE8E1&\bord0\blur1\pos(1125,316)}Kiska Volcano
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.17,0:02:03.10,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1500,2000)\c&HFCE8E1&\bord1\blur1\pos(975,620)}Kiska Bay
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.17,0:02:03.10,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1500,2000)\c&HFCE8E1&\bord1\blur1\pos(1111,780)}Little Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.93,0:01:59.27,Default,,0,0,0,,But the Aleutian Operation achieved the occupation of Attu and Kiska without any resistance from the US whatsoever.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:56.15,0:02:03.08,Sign,,0,0,300,,{\fade(700,2000)\b1\blur1\bord0\c&HF6E9E5&}Episode 16 \N{\fs110}Evacuation of Kiska
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.09,0:02:09.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Kiska Island is about 40 km long and 10 km wide.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.54,0:02:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,It is enclosed in ice and snow all year round. {to shut in (with snow, ice, etc.); to shut off; to cut off; to cover (e.g. in darkness)​}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.19,0:02:19.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Even in the summer, a thick fog enshrouds it \Nwith the temperatures often dropping below freezing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.61,0:02:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Originally, the Japanese operational goals for the Aleutians
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.10,0:02:28.23,Default,,0,0,0,,were to deny the use of the northern naval bases \Nby American task forces. {lit: to prevent the attack of american TF from north/shore up the northern flank}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.71,0:02:34.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Here, on Kiska Island, the northern sea garrison commander Major General Mineki
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.05,0:02:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,was stationed with about 5,600 Army and Navy personnel.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.85,0:02:42.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.15,0:02:46.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The Northern Army's reconnaissance aircraft reports:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.22,0:02:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,apparently, at some point, the enemy built \Nan air base on the neighboring island of Amchitka.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.95,0:02:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,What?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.71,0:02:58.28,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, the Americans went on the offensive everywhere \Nafter the battle of Guadalcanal in the south.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.28,0:03:00.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Have they finally reached the north too?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.47,0:03:04.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Amchitka is about 90 nautical miles away from Kiska.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.47,0:03:03.47,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H361815&\pos(490,206)}Attu
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.47,0:03:03.47,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H361815&\pos(746,484)}Kiska
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.47,0:03:03.47,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H361815&\pos(1082,729)}Amchitka
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.12,0:03:07.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Naturally, the air raids on Attu Island \Nwill also be more intense now.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.71,0:03:15.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Kiska and Attu are important northern bases for us. \NWe have to protect them at all costs.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.42,0:03:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Air raid!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.47,0:03:46.46,Default,,0,0,0,,The Imperial Headquarters immediately began bringing in \Nreinforcements to Attu Island and Kiska Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.71,0:03:50.98,Default,,0,0,0,,On May 11th,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.98,0:03:56.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Escorted by the US North Pacific fleet \Nunder Rear Admiral Thomas C. Kinkaid, {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_C._Kinkaid#Aleutian_Islands}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.32,0:03:59.61,Default,,0,0,0,,approximately 11,000 US troops
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.61,0:04:02.10,Default,,0,0,0,,began landing on Attu Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.21,0:04:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Commanded by Colonel Yamazaki, the garrison \Nof about 2,500 Japanese soldiers fought back fiercely.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.11,0:04:15.13,Default,,0,0,0,,But on May 30th, at last, it was annihilated.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.77,0:04:20.13,Default,,0,0,0,,For the first time, the Japanese Army \Nused the phrase "honorable death" to describe this event. {The annihilation of the Attu Island garrison was reported for the first time in Japan using the word `` gyokusai, '' and it caused a great shock to the people . [14] - "banzai charge" kinda works but it wasn't the first one and besides the japanese wouldn't call it that}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.07,0:04:25.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The US Army that recaptured \NAttu Island from the Japanese,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.30,0:04:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,set up a naval blockade in the Northern Pacific \Nto starve out the isolated island of Kiska.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.71,0:04:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, the Imperial Headquarters approved the evacuation of the isolated island of Kiska with submarines.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.44,0:04:42.25,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, the retreat order was issued.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.25,0:04:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The US Pacific Fleet watched the island closely, \Nmaking any evacuation efforts extremely difficult.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.02,0:04:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy attacks are more intense by the day.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.00,0:05:00.03,Default,,0,0,0,,It's only a matter of time before they land on Kiska too.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.20,0:05:05.61,Default,,0,0,0,,We must complete the evacuation \Nof the island garrison before that happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.61,0:05:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy is on high alert.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.34,0:05:10.24,Default,,0,0,0,,They already sunk several of our submarines.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.24,0:05:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,How many have escaped via submarines?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.04,0:05:17.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Out of 5,639 men...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.40,0:05:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,820.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.46,0:05:20.55,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.53,0:05:23.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So only 15%? {1割5分か - seems kinda wild that a military officer can or will just count percentage on a spur like this, but because it actually is 1/7 or about 15%, kinda believing HA; I suspect it's actually "1/5" but 5600 is clearly way above 4000 so unlikely}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.07,0:05:27.39,Default,,0,0,0,,A submarine can only take \Nup to 80 men on board at a time.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.39,0:05:28.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Staff Officer Fujii. {believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.39,0:05:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.39,0:05:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Head to Paramushir. {really sounds more like koromushi but has to be it}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.84,0:05:35.77,Default,,0,0,0,,I need you to convince the Northern Army Headquarters \Nto evacuate the island all at once with the surface fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.77,0:05:37.73,Default,,0,0,0,,This needs to be done as soon as possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.40,0:05:41.71,Default,,0,0,0,,This is probably the last time \Nwe can speak on the matter of evacuation.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.36,0:05:51.49,Default,,0,0,0,,On June 16th, the submarine carrying Staff Officer Fujii \Nsafely left the Kiska waters.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.49,0:05:55.25,Default,,0,0,0,,On the 20th, it arrived at Paramushir on Kuril Islands.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.14,0:05:59.73,Default,,0,0,0,,In the Paramushir port, \Npart of the Northern Fleet,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.73,0:06:04.13,Default,,0,0,0,,the 5th Fleet, under the command \Nof Vice Admiral Kawase was anchored. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiro_Kawase}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.72,0:06:11.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The local commander urges for an evacuation \Nby means of the surface fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.83,0:06:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The way things have been up to now,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.75,0:06:20.31,Default,,0,0,0,,our submarine fleet took a serious beating.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.73,0:06:23.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The evacuation via submarines has to stop either way.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.74,0:06:30.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Will a large enough fleet really be able to sneak \Npast the enemy's watchful eye and make it to Kiska?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.62,0:06:31.96,Default,,0,0,0,,That is the main problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.96,0:06:34.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Add to that, there's no hope for air cover.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.10,0:06:38.73,Default,,0,0,0,,This plan
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.35,0:06:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,is straight-up madness.{/reckless}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.52,0:06:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,On Kiska, 5,000 of our comrades \Nare holding out in spite of the enemy onslaught.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.88,0:06:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Was one Attu Island not enough? {lit: you want to get the repetition of Attu}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.57,0:06:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,It takes 10 days at least to get to Kiska and return.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.32,0:06:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Because any large formation would have to bring along a tanker,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.50,0:06:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,this operation is unfeasible by the surface fleet. {王女隊の艦艇が行動することは航海上から考えても 不可能になるでしょうが - "without bringing along a tanker for replenishment, for a large formation, performing such a maneuver is close to impossible if you think about it from on high seas"}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.00,0:07:01.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't say I have much confidence in our navy.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.91,0:07:12.91,Default,,0,0,0,,If only we had someone who could thread the needle \Nwith such a big formation, we could do it. {to manage; to control; to run; to handle}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.49,0:07:16.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, in our entire fleet...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.98,0:07:25.71,Default,,0,0,0,,There is one.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.97,0:07:32.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Call him. Kimura the Mustache. {lit is "beard's kimura" but he didn't exactly have beard, but a stache and japanese doesn't have a word for that; this nickname has no english translation yet}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.41,0:07:37.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Rear Admiral Kimura was the seafarer who transferred his flag to the light cruiser Abukuma some mere 10 days ago {lit is "assumed a new post at the flagship abukuma, a man of the sea" whatever that means}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.59,0:07:41.23,Default,,0,0,0,,to assume command of the 1st Destroyer Flotilla. \NHe was known as Kimura the Mustache. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masatomi_Kimura}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.12,0:07:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I accept it. {the assignment}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.49,0:07:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.68,0:07:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,You'd do us a great favor.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.02,0:07:50.61,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy has excellent radar at their disposal.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.11,0:07:52.91,Default,,0,0,0,,We also have an ace up our sleeves. {lit: we/I also have a strategy/plan}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.39,0:07:54.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.41,0:07:57.91,Default,,0,0,0,,It's one of Japan's oldest stealth techniques: \Ndisappearing into the mist. {/hiding ... ninjutsu; combat and stealth techniques used by ninja for espionage, sabotage, assassination, etc.​ - https://www.weblio.jp/content/%E9%9C%A7%E9%9A%A0%E3%82%8C%E3%81%AE%E8%A1%93}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.91,0:07:59.15,Default,,0,0,0,,What?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.82,0:08:03.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The fog is thick around Kiska Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.22,0:08:06.04,Default,,0,0,0,,If we make use of the fog, \Nwe'll have the upper hand.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.04,0:08:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.13,0:08:20.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the daring plan for the evacuation of Kiska that relied solely on the North Sea fog, was set in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.52,0:08:24.50,Default,,0,0,0,,In an evacuation operation, \Nthe fog is our closest ally.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.50,0:08:26.89,Default,,0,0,0,,But this fog will become thinner by August.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.89,0:08:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,If we're doing it, we have to complete it by mid-July.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.49,0:08:32.69,Default,,0,0,0,,How many Daihatsu-class boats do they have there? {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daihatsu-class_landing_craft}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.69,0:08:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably around 10 are operable.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.38,0:08:38.18,Default,,0,0,0,,If so, boarding alone would take a long time. \NAlright, let's carry them on 12 ships. {lit: With so few of them, transporting the troops will take time. Alright, let's load 12 ships. - not sure what he means; それだけじゃ輸送に時間がかかる よし 12隻積んでいこう}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.18,0:08:42.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The biggest hurdle here is appointing \Nthe location and time for our rendezvous with the troops.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.87,0:08:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,If we choose the wrong spot, \Nwe won't make it out of Kiska alive. {集合地点を間違えばキスカ島に接近できても - no clue what he means by I think there's something else he wants to say so there should be "..." on the end so he means "if the meeting point is poorly picked, even if we manage to approach Kiska, [we won't be able to leave it]"}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.73,0:08:48.28,Default,,0,0,0,,The venue is Kiska Bay.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.48,0:08:53.19,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H221819&\pos(290,618)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.48,0:08:53.19,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H221819&\pos(763,402)}Kiska Bay
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.48,0:08:53.19,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&H221819&\pos(919,672)}Little Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.28,0:08:53.17,Default,,0,0,0,,The rendezvous time \Nis 5 days after our Rescue Fleet sails.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.17,0:08:55.18,Default,,0,0,0,,In the next 3 hours after the sun sets.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.18,0:08:57.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And if the fog clears and we can't approach Kiska? { on that day}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.43,0:09:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Tell them to be prepared for it every day at the same time.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.20,0:09:03.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Evacuation is a covert operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.97,0:09:06.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Exercise extreme caution when contacting them.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.33,0:09:21.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The Rescue Fleet sets sail from Paramushir on July 7th.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.16,0:09:25.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Our garrison will assemble at Kiska Port \Nat sunset on the 11th.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.33,0:09:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Do not leave a single soldier behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.62,0:09:42.91,Default,,0,0,0,,When will the rescue fleet make it here?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.87,0:09:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They won't come here just for us. {lit: they can't come that easily}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.00,0:09:49.29,Default,,0,0,0,,They're leaving us to the same fate as Attu.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.65,0:09:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,July 7th, 1943. The Rescue Fleet \Nunder Major General Kimura,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.31,0:10:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,composed of 2 light cruisers, 10 destroyers, \None tanker, and one escort ship. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaib%C5%8Dkan}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.64,0:10:08.19,Default,,0,0,0,,With a total of 14 ships, \Nthey left from Paramushir Port on the Kuril Islands.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.47,0:10:13.82,Default,,0,0,0,,The fog looks excellent.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.82,0:10:16.15,Default,,0,0,0,,No, don't get too optimistic just yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.15,0:10:19.64,Default,,0,0,0,,But even under the cover of fog, \Nif the enemy spots us, our goose is cooked. {unsure what's harebakara}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.64,0:10:22.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Stay 500 nautical miles away \Nfrom the enemy air base.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.58,0:10:35.57,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\pos(614,154)\c&HEADEEB&}Attu Island
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.58,0:10:35.57,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&HEADEEB&\pos(868,253)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.58,0:10:35.57,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord0\blur1\c&HEADEEB&\pos(745,754)}Japanese Fleet
Dialogue: 1,0:10:23.71,0:10:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,As planned, the rescue fleet has reached the point \N500 nautical miles southwest of Kiska on July 12th.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:30.70,0:10:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,After refueling, they set course for Kiska.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:35.57,0:10:39.76,Default,,0,0,0,,However, when it was time to carry out \Nthe evacuation, the fog cleared up.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.23,0:10:43.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed, what is it if not an ironic quirk of nature? {/prank}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.36,0:10:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.85,0:10:56.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Our resolve is to do it or die trying. {lit: we made it this far prepared for death}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.09,0:10:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's do it!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.10,0:11:07.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. All the ships are urging to break formation. {no clue what's issen, no clue what he means by "rushing into; breaking into; storming​/plunging into (war, etc.); embarking on (a new venture)"; wisper conveniently had a stroke on this line and HA has it "they are urging you to come all at once." so issen is apparently "all at once" but it still doesn't make sense; what I hear is "they are urging for you to rush into all at once" so I think what he means is, in fog they assumed a line formation - one after another, but without fog they're proposing to dissolve it and rush to the destination in the normal formation - "blob"}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.15,0:11:11.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The fog might return by the time we get to Kiska.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.46,0:11:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Why don't we return to safety \Nand wait for another chance? {actually "point of standing by; awaiting an opportunity; being on alert/point of waiting" but it's too cps heavy}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.01,0:11:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Impossible. We haven't enough fuel.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.49,0:11:22.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, why don't we withdraw to Paramushir \Nand try again another day? {no clue what's futsuzari here}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.89,0:11:24.35,Default,,0,0,0,,We won't be able to do that either.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.35,0:11:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,With current fuel shortages, \Nthey won't have enough for a formation this big. {lit: fuel shortage is a present condition; existing state; status quo; current state, to make a second attempt with a fleet this sizeable}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.49,0:11:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Are we marooning the Kiska garrison, then?! {/leaving to death}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.47,0:11:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.95,0:12:03.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, what's your call? {/decision}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.71,0:12:15.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn back.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.53,0:12:22.18,Default,,0,0,0,,If we turn back now, \Nwe can come again another time.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.25,0:12:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Later that day, the Kiska garrison, \Nwaiting intently for the appearance of the rescue fleet,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.71,0:12:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,received a telegram, \Nsignaling the cancellation of their evacuation. {ryakuden is usually "biographical sketch" but has to be "short telegram"}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.15,0:12:40.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Once again, the Kiska garrison plunged into desperation.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.63,0:12:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The scenes of their comrades on Attu Island going down in a banzai charge
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.85,0:12:49.70,Default,,0,0,0,,were brought back to life in their imagination.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.35,0:13:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.49,0:13:08.49,Default,,0,0,0,,How about this?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.85,0:13:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Making use of this opportunity, why don't I move here?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.10,0:13:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, don't mind me attacking here.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.16,0:13:17.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Good move, but it's too little too late. {lit: at that time, already late - no clue what he means}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.87,0:13:29.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? Well, that's quite a pickle! \NI was a little careless there.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.39,0:13:35.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Spotting the enemy's carelessness \Nand exploiting it is the key to victory.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.70,0:13:36.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.94,0:13:38.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.87,0:13:39.77,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.63,0:13:43.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The sea between Paramushir and Aleutians is in fog.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.01,0:13:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,How many days will it last?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.88,0:13:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. Five days...? Probably five days at least.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.84,0:13:49.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.09,0:13:50.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that so?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.69,0:13:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,What day is it today?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.81,0:13:54.75,Default,,0,0,0,,July 19th, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.31,0:13:56.25,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.49,0:14:06.23,Default,,0,0,0,,At this point, let us leapfrog to the events of July 30th, \Nabout 10 days after July 19th,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.23,0:14:09.34,Default,,0,0,0,,so as to peek at the situation on the American side.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.89,0:14:17.64,Default,,0,0,0,,From the 30th on, the American North Pacific Fleet \Nwas pounding Kiska daily with naval artillery fire.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.34,0:14:22.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The US Commandos were finally about to invade Kiska.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.34,0:14:29.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The Kiska Island environs were entirely blockaded \Nby the American North Pacific Fleet,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.16,0:14:34.01,Default,,0,0,0,,rendering any possible relief efforts \Nof the Japanese fleet utterly futile.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.24,0:14:41.01,Default,,0,0,0,,On August 14th, the US Army \Nfinally launched the landings on Kiska.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.43,0:14:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,A total of 91 ships supported the landing.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.15,0:14:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Over 34,000 troops took part in the operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.85,0:15:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Where the hell did the Japanese go?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.31,0:15:50.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably headed for the hills. {/escaped to mountains or hills}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.92,0:16:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,On Kiska Island, they found nothing but 3 stray dogs. \NThe Japanese garrison evacuated in full.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.97,0:16:21.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In this operation, due to multiple instances of friendly fire \Nerupting from tension and panic among the troops,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.81,0:16:24.75,Default,,0,0,0,,the American losses were 25 dead and 31 wounded.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.27,0:16:28.27,Default,,0,0,0,,In a major blockade running operation,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.27,0:16:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the entire 5,000-strong Japanese garrison was evacuated to safety from right under the nose of the US Fleet. {pretty liberal: about 5000 of japanese gar. escaped the watchful eye of american blockade - when did they withdraw?}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.50,0:16:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,The mystery of their escape \Nwas shrouded in thick North Sea fog. {lit: the n.s. fog would cover everything in deep mystery}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.23,0:16:45.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us once again return \Nto the Japanese perspective on July 19th.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.38,0:16:47.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.48,0:16:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.99,0:16:51.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The sea between Paramushir and Aleutians is covered in fog.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.48,0:16:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,How many days will it last?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.84,0:16:55.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. In any case, I believe \Nthis is the final fog of the summer.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.43,0:16:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.01,0:16:59.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that so?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.21,0:17:00.41,Default,,0,0,0,,What day is it today?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.83,0:17:01.96,Default,,0,0,0,,July 19th, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.55,0:17:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,On July 22nd, just as the thick fog reappeared, the Rescue Fleet left Paramushir for the second evacuation operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.61,0:17:20.79,Default,,0,0,0,,This fog is perfect for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.79,0:17:22.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's just hope it doesn't clear up.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.27,0:17:29.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Aboard the light cruiser Kiso, Staff officer Fujii \Nprayed for the safety of his comrades on Kiska Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.24,0:17:37.13,Default,,0,0,0,,This time for sure, we'll pull it off \Nwithout a hitch. Just you wait.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.69,0:17:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,If the enemy lands, these fellows ain't having it easy. {/I feel sorry for them - meaning dogs}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.42,0:17:50.53,Default,,0,0,0,,You guys make sure to survive, you hear? {not sure why he says "only you guys"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.38,0:17:54.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The rescue fleet set sail from Paramushir!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.26,0:17:55.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you sure?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.42,0:17:57.07,Default,,0,0,0,,We're finally going home this time!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.81,0:17:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it true?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.56,0:17:59.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank god!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.70,0:18:01.23,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm fed up with Kiska! {no clue what's last word}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.23,0:18:03.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I received a telegram saying they left today! {nc whats gyakuten, gotta be telegram}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.08,0:18:07.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The men of the Kiska Island garrison were delighted.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.58,0:18:14.80,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the entrance to Kiska Bay \Nwas still observed closely by two American destroyers.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.03,0:18:19.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Around that time, one American reconnaissance plane
Dialogue: 1,0:18:19.64,0:18:25.93,Default,,0,0,0,,detected with its radar what seemed like seven Japanese ships 200 nautical miles southwest of Attu Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.72,0:18:30.65,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\fade(0500,0)\pos(427,310)\3c&H825F4A&}Attu Island
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.72,0:18:30.65,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\fade(0500,0)\3c&H825F4A&\pos(1093,574)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 1,0:18:25.93,0:18:32.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The US North Pacific Fleet gathered at the point designated by the reconnaissance plane on July 25th,
Dialogue: 1,0:18:32.67,0:18:34.86,Default,,0,0,0,,prepared to ambush the Japanese fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.22,0:18:41.64,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1000,0)\bord1\blur1\pos(276,426)}Attu Island
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.22,0:18:41.64,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1000,0)\bord1\blur1\pos(1049,730)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.22,0:18:41.64,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(1000,0)\bord1\blur1\pos(556,662)}American North Pacific Fleet
Dialogue: 1,0:18:35.61,0:18:41.66,Default,,0,0,0,,However, as it turned out later, \Nthey unleashed hell on a Japanese ghost fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.31,0:18:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The American fleet, operating the reconnaissance plane \Nnever realized their radar malfunctioned.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.87,0:19:04.47,Default,,0,0,0,,What their radar mistook for the Japanese fleet \Nwas just an echo from a nearby island.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.03,0:19:13.98,Default,,0,0,0,,In this attack, the US Fleet bombarded \Nthe cold North Pacific waters with over 1,000 shells.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.11,0:19:17.96,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, the Japanese Rescue Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.90,0:19:23.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\pos(682,762)}Japanese Rescue Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.90,0:19:23.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\pos(602,156)}Attu Island
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.90,0:19:23.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\pos(863,246)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.96,0:19:21.34,Default,,0,0,0,,was leisurely resupplying and biding its time
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.34,0:19:26.95,Default,,0,0,0,,at a distant point about 500 nautical miles \Nsouthwest of Kiska Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.95,0:19:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Dammit! The fog cleared up again.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.93,0:19:37.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Second verse same as the first. {/Same as the first time.}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.84,0:19:41.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe we were too late \Nand the foggy season has elapsed already?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.74,0:19:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, if we keep things as is, \Nan enemy scout plane will spot us in no time.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.69,0:19:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,If we come under attack, it's over for us!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.06,0:19:50.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.30,0:19:54.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The Kiska Island garrison contacted us.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.52,0:19:58.63,Default,,0,0,0,,They report that the weather on the 29th \Nis definitely going to be foggy.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.63,0:20:02.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, it's hardly believable \Nthat such fine weather can turn into fog.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.93,0:20:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,No, it's a prime opportunity.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.30,0:20:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,March towards the Kiska Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.51,0:20:16.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.73,0:20:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,That's like jumping straight into the enemy's claws. {actually "pocket"}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.46,0:20:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,If the enemy fleet appears, we'll engage them, \Nbuying time to complete the evacuation. {lit: in the meantime, conduct the evac.}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.37,0:20:27.50,Top,,0,0,0,,On July 29th,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.76,0:20:47.78,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\c&HE6EEEB&\pos(310,258)}Attu Island
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.76,0:20:47.78,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\c&HE6EEEB&\pos(484,416)}American North Pacific Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.76,0:20:47.78,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\c&HE6EEEB&\pos(967,514)}Kiska Island
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.76,0:20:47.78,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\bord1\blur1\c&HE6EEEB&\pos(612,962)}Japanese Rescue Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.50,0:20:31.55,Top,,0,0,0,,miraculously, the fog once again \Ncovered the North Pacific.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.55,0:20:35.94,Top,,0,0,0,,The attack on the Japanese ghost fleet exhausted their fuel,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.94,0:20:38.61,Top,,0,0,0,,so all ships of the US North Pacific Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.61,0:20:46.57,Top,,0,0,0,,gathered at a point 105 nautical miles south-southeast of Kiska Island, preparing to refuel.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.57,0:20:52.62,Top,,0,0,0,,Thus, it so happened that Kiska Island \Nwas not watched at that exact moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.99,0:20:59.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly as Rear Admiral Kimura planned, \Nthe rescue fleet rushed through the fog into Kiska Bay. {actually "decided"}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.51,0:21:24.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Ships are coming!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.53,0:21:26.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Japanese ships are here! {nc whats last word}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.65,0:21:41.88,Default,,0,0,0,,They came for us. We can go home now!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.13,0:21:51.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, can you see it?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.47,0:21:53.17,Default,,0,0,0,,The happy faces of our men!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.48,0:21:58.17,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a relief. Such a relief!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.53,0:22:26.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The last Daihatsu boat left the shore!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.14,0:22:37.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Major General, thank you for your patience. {still assuming it's Major General Mineki}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.13,0:22:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,You did well.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.61,0:22:47.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The Kiska Island garrison of about 5,000 men evacuated without leaving a single man behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.90,0:22:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The whole operation took a mere 55 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.54,0:23:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you really call this, the evacuation of Kiska, that'll stay in the annals of military history, just a stroke of luck?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.39,0:23:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,During the first evacuation attempt,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.59,0:23:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,had Rear Admiral Kimura made a reckless choice \Nand decided to risk it,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.99,0:23:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,he'd unmistakeably end up drawing the attention \Nof the watchful US Fleet and getting annihilated.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.19,0:23:26.29,Default,,0,0,0,,A commander cannot afford to lose his composure \Neven when worse comes to worst. {lit: even in the worst possible case, can't lose his cool judgment}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.29,0:23:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Only when he looks at all the possibilities \Nand makes composed decisions that lead to success,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.22,0:23:36.57,Default,,0,0,0,,can a commander's true merit be manifested.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.04,0:23:44.36,Default,,0,0,0,,On August 1st, the rescue fleet \Nmade it safely to the Paramushir Port.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.54,0:23:52.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Even after that, the US Fleet continued to bombard \Nthe ghost garrison on Kiska Island just like before,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.82,0:23:55.79,Default,,0,0,0,,inspiring great fear in three left behind dogs.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.08,0:24:07.82,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.69,0:24:12.21,Default,,0,0,0,,October 1944.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.21,0:24:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,In the face of the great number or relentlessly advancing US troops,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.93,0:24:20.89,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese Army decides to unleash an unprecedented ramming attack on the military forces of the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.89,0:24:23.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Christened as the Special Kamikaze Squadron,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.54,0:24:28.32,Default,,0,0,0,,While praying for the safety of the motherland \Nand carrying 250 kg bombs underneath,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.32,0:24:31.95,Default,,0,0,0,,a great many young men \Nlose their lives in pursuit of the enemy carrier.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.95,0:24:38.21,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 17\NBirth of Kamikaze Corps {特攻隊誕生}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.95,0:24:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Witness the next week's decision: \NBirth of Kamikaze Corps.
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.17,0:24:48.92,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
